The paper deals with information theory and its applications, specifically in the context of codebooks and joint distributions. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses typical sets, which falls under cs.ITP (Information Theory and Probability). The use of the covering lemma in rate-distortion theory and multi-user channels suggests that cs.MM (Multimedia) and cs.SI (Signal and Image Processing) are also possible sub-categories. Finally, the paper's focus on codebooks and joint distributions may also make it relevant to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
